    pearls: ["Left axis deviation on ECG in a cyanotic neonate is highly suggestive of tricuspid atresia — neonates normally have right axis deviation; this ECG finding helps distinguish tricuspid atresia from other cyanotic CHDs","Prostaglandin E1 is LIFE-SAVING for ductal-dependent lesions — never discontinue without surgical backup; the most serious side effect is APNEA (keep intubation equipment at bedside at all times)","The single-ventricle surgical pathway (BT shunt → Glenn → Fontan) creates a circulatory system where systemic venous blood flows PASSIVELY through the lungs — there is no right ventricular pump; this depends on low pulmonary vascular resistance","After a BT shunt, the continuous MURMUR indicates shunt patency — ABSENCE of the murmur is an EMERGENCY suggesting shunt thrombosis and loss of pulmonary blood flow","Fontan physiology creates unique long-term complications: protein-losing enteropathy (PLE), plastic bronchitis, Fontan-associated liver disease (FALD), and arrhythmias — lifelong cardiac follow-up is essential","Target oxygen saturations vary by surgical stage: pre-operative mixing may have SpO2 of 75-85%; post-Glenn 80-85%; post-Fontan 90-95% — do NOT aim for 100% as this suggests a shunt or additional source of pulmonary blood flow","Feeding these infants requires patience and high-calorie strategies: fortified formula (24-30 kcal/oz), frequent small feeds, and monitoring for feeding fatigue (diaphoresis, tachypnea during feeds) which indicates excessive cardiac work"],
